Chapter 1
Colren
It was 4:30 a.m. in Colren's time zone, and Colren hated getting up this early. It was mainly because he had to wake up the rest of the platoon. He quietly got out of bed, put on his combat outfit, zipped up his tactical vest, and carefully picked up a small special box from his storage cabinet. He slung his rifle over his shoulder, hung his helmet from a small hook on his belt, and checked the equipment on his helmet, which included an oxygen tank, goggles, and other essential items. After he checked the ammunition bag, he quietly walked out of the barracks, his boots making squelching and crunching sounds on the wet and icy ground.
He pulled out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff, then opened the door. In the past week, he had to rack his brain to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, as half the time it didn't ring, and all that could be heard from the loudspeaker was a weak buzzing sound.
“Time to wake them up?” Colren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemiche approaching.
“Yes.” Kuren replied.
“What are you going to do this time?”
Kuren hadn't even had a chance to answer before the door opened and Harris, Kreis, and the others rushed out, already dressed and ready to go.
“Good morning,” said Kreis.
“What woke you up this morning?” Kuren asked.
“First, we really don't want to see what you're going to use to wake everyone up today. Secondly, the first squad to wake up can enjoy breakfast first,” replied a soldier named Ravik. “You know, those breakfasts are truly terrible.”
Cullen said, “You're right, Ravik. He pressed the switch with his hand. The camp suddenly reverberated with a shrill alarm sound. He heard loud shouting from inside, accompanied by a series of frantic footsteps.”
“Heaven's sake, Valtor,” Nemich said. “I thought they should have learned to wake up with you by now.”
“My brother in the recruit training camp has done so,” Cullen pointed at Harris, Kress, and Ravik. “But, after all, their platoon leader and company commander know to wake up before the soldiers wake up.”
A few seconds later, the rest of the soldiers in the squad emerged. They all wore their uniforms neatly and were ready. Some new recruits looked sleepy, while others seemed very annoyed.
"Good morning," Colonel Crenshaw said with a cheerful grin.
"To be frank, sir, why did you have to wake us up that way?" a sergeant of the special forces team asked.
"Because regular alarm clocks are junk, and Daybreak never sleeps in," Crenshaw replied.
"Take your personal belongings," Crenshaw continued, as a lieutenant and second-in-command of the platoon, he had the duty to assist the platoon commander, Lieutenant Broladin Xao, in supervising and leading the platoon. "We won't be back. Gentlemen sergeants and lieutenants, you have 15 minutes to make a final check and bring the rations needed for today."
The members of Exodus platoon quickly parted ways. They were part of the 2nd Assault Division's 2nd Assault Brigade. Before the merger, they were originally two independent platoons, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite platoon, and Crenshaw felt complex about his promotion to lieutenant. There were many reasons for that.
Kolen and First Lieutenant Nimitch walked side by side on the brightly lit road in the base, the lights on both sides of the road were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, which could help them avoid enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak had begun to adopt the "Wild Mouse" tactics in the air and on the ground.
"New day, new mission for Hell's Fury." Nimitch smiled wryly. "Where are they sending us off to this time?"
"Ialos City outside, some forward base on the front line. We're going to support the ground assault," Kolen said, taking a drag on his cigarette. He was a bit resentful that Kress had gotten him hooked on cigarettes, but thinking about the past year, they had experienced countless battles, so he let it slide, and said nothing.
"Terrible. The front line is getting tough," Nimitch said in a low voice. "All the news coming out of here is 'Support the war, aid the Kurgan Front', why not support the Harlan Front instead?"
"Well said, brother," Kolen said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We're walking with the First Armored Platoon, no need to walk. Lieutenant Shaw should be there."
“What's the story with Lieutenant Shaw wanting us to hitch a ride?”
“Yes, to be honest, he's not as bad as I thought he'd be. I mean, he's not exactly great, but he's not that annoying either.”
Colón raised his thumb and index finger, pressing a microphone against his throat while moving his backpack to his back. “Exodus, all units, assemble at Western Vehicle Park after completing the mission. We'll depart at 05:00 with the First Armored Platoon.”
Every few seconds, he received a reply from the sergeants. They had all been low-ranking corporals when they first arrived, Harris, Kress, and Ravik, but since their basic training on Earth, the four of them had been the best of friends. Colón felt like it had been years since they met, even though it had only been less than two years. They were all sergeants now, but since last week when the platoon leader was hit by Daybreak snipers and retired due to injury, Kress had taken over as the leader of the second platoon.
As they walked to the vehicle park, Colón and Nimitz's gaze fell on about eight Chronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored cars. Crew members were rushing about to ensure their war machines were in working order. Colón quickly spotted Lieutenant Shaw among the crowd, talking to the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Shaw looked at them and came over, his usual expressionless face giving away no emotion.
“Nimitz Lieutenant……Vartorri Lieutenant……” he said, Crenshaw slowed down his pace, Crenshaw looked at Crenshaw's pistol holster, then looked up. “Has the platoon been prepared yet?”
